  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau is not a local optimum problem—it is a **dimensionality ceiling**. Evolution has saturated the current phenotype space and fitness criteria. The system is not stuck because organisms are bad at searching; it is stuck because all searchable directions lead to the same fitness value. Structural changes that *expand the search space itself* (new state dimensions, new beauty criteria, new environmental conditions) are the only way through. Parameter tweaking within current dimensions will never restart growth.; [medium] Introduce organism internal state machines with persistent memory across timesteps. Organisms carry registers (counters, toggles, accumulators) that modify their sensorimotor logic. Decision functions become state-dependent: same input → different output depending on internal state. — Current organisms are likely stateless reactors—stimulus directly triggers response. Plateau occurs because all stateless strategies are exhausted. State machines unlock entirely new behavior spaces: temporal strategies, behavioral phases, learned-like responses. This multiplies the decision-function dimensionality without new cell types.; [easy] Introduce multi-scale beauty scoring: add new dimensions beyond current metrics. Measure local order (cell-neighborhood coherence), temporal consistency (smoothness of motion/shape change), and symmetry breaking (asymmetric structures that resolve resource conflicts). Weight these dynamically per organism generation to prevent convergence to a single beauty attractor. — Beauty plateau likely means all organisms are optimizing toward the same beauty mode. Multiple, sometimes conflicting beauty dimensions force exploration of different phenotypic spaces. An organism beautiful by one measure (symmetry) may be ugly by another (local adaptability), preventing monoculture convergence.; [hard] Implement dynamic world physics: add periodic environmental cycles (light intensity, nutrient distribution, temperature zones) with 20-50 timestep periods. Fitness depends on performance across multiple world states, not just one. Organisms that excel in one state but fail in another lower their composite score. — Static worlds favor convergence to a single strategy. Cyclic environments reward organisms that adapt or maintain robustness. This breaks the plateau because no single morphology can simultaneously optimize for all states—evolution must explore trades between states, reopening the solution space. New beauty emerges: phase-locking, resource-seasonality adaptation.",
